Hypothesis Testing

Two sided-test

Null Hypothesis H0: There is no significant difference in the average salaries of male and female employees. Alternative Hypothesis HA: There is a significant difference in the average salaries of male and female workers.

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Salary by Gender
## t = -5.4232, df = 991.2, p-value = 7.354e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Female and group Male is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -11578.176  -5425.519
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Female   mean in group Male 
##             96416.83            104918.68

Since p-value is very small, the null hypothesis that there is no significant difference between the salaries of male and female employees is rejected.

One-sided t-test (test if males earn more)

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Salary by Gender
## t = -5.4232, df = 991.2, p-value = 3.677e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Female and group Male is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -5920.852
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Female   mean in group Male 
##             96416.83            104918.68

Since p-value is very small, the null hypothesis that there is no significant difference between the salaries of male and female employees is rejected.

Insights

Males earn about $8,749 more on average than females in comparable roles after controlling for education, department, and seniority.

Seniority has the largest impact on pay.

Education and department also affect salary.

Boxplots and scatterplots clearly show disparities in pay between genders.
